                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d943">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867.00/3129: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-25T21:00:00-04:00"
                            >March 25, 1942—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>139. Your 85, March 24, 8 p.m. You may inform the Vice Commissar that Steinhardt
                    has already mentioned the report in question to the Turkish authorities. The
                    Department would have no objection to the report being mentioned by the Soviet
                    Government in discussions with the Turkish Government. In such discussions,
                    however, it should be clearly understood that although the report emanated from
                    a source <pb facs="0840" n="828" xml:id="pg_828"/> which at times has been found
                    to be reliable, the American Government is not in a position to confirm it and,
                    therefore, cannot be responsible for its authenticity.</p>
                <p>You should make clear that no public reference which might be made to this report
                    should indicate that it has come through an American source.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
